n kin, as she reflects on the resilient work that Indigenous creative work has done and continues to do in spite of colonial violence. She stakes a claim for the necessity of poetry in the face of ongoing colonialism, not only in the present but in the future and for the generations to come. The introduction by Dallas Hunt locates Akiwenzie-Damm within the field of Indigenous literature and meditates on her influence on the field of Indigenous erotica. Kateri Akiwenzie-Damm writes in service of Indigenous brilliance, love, intimacy, and joy, and speaks with an unwavering voice, one that, to paraphrase Akiwenzie-Damm herself, “shakes the earth.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetryy20th century. 0aCanadian poetryy21st century. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aPoetry. 4aSocial Science: Women’s studies. 7aPOETRY / Canadian / Indigenous.2bisacsh  aAnishinaabe.  aCanada studies.  aCanadian literature.  aCree.  aDallas Hunt.  aIndigenous erotica.  aIndigenous literature.  aIndigenous poetry.  aIndigenous poets.  aIndigenous studies.  aKateri Akiwenzie-Damm.  aKegedonce.  aPoetry.  aSovereign erotic.  aSovereign erotics.  awho are some Indigenous poets.1 aHunt, Dallas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112473740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771124737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771124737/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles